n1: deceptive appearances
	summary=To the naked eye the universe is a few thousand dots and hazy streaks; a conjuring trick looks like magic. Appearances are not self-explanatory.
n2: hidden reality
	summary=Behind the dots, nuclear furnaces millions of kilometres wide and light years away. Behind winter, the geometry of a tilted, orbiting planet. None of it is ever directly observed.
n3: explanatory theory
	summary=A claim about what is really out there and how it behaves, a statement of the reality that accounts for the appearance. Not a summary of observations.
n4: the knowledge problem
	summary=How can theories that begin as local guesswork inside one brain, tested only locally, contain accurate knowledge of a reality we have never experienced?
n5: empiricism
	summary=The misconception that we derive knowledge from the senses. Locke's mind as 'white paper', nature as a 'Book' to be read. The discoverer as passive recipient, not creator.
n6: sensory authority
	summary=Experience installed as the authoritative source of theories, replacing holy books and priests while keeping the same authority-shaped mistake.
n7: inductivism
	summary=The misconception that repeating an experience under similar circumstances lets you generalize it into a theory or a reliable prediction.
n8: the principle of induction
	summary=The future will resemble the past; the unseen resembles the seen. No one has ever stated a version usable to obtain a theory from experience.
n9: the logical gap
	summary=No deduction from statements about experiences can reach a conclusion about anything other than those experiences. You cannot deduce Mars from a map of Earth.
n10: the deceptiveness of the senses
	summary=For millennia the rotating 'celestial sphere' was directly observed and repeatedly confirmed, yet it does not exist. The senses say nothing; only our fallible interpretations do.
n11: justificationism
	summary=The older, deeper disease, that knowledge needs authority to be genuine, justified true belief. It turns 'how do we know?' into 'by what authority do we claim?'.
n12: conjecture
	summary=The real source of all theories. Minds rearrange, combine and alter existing ideas to improve them. Discovering an explanation is an act of creativity, not derivation.
n13: criticism
	summary=Error-correction. Exposing an idea to objections and tests, asking whether it solves the problem without smuggling in arbitrary detail.
n14: theory-laden observation
	summary=There is no raw data. Nerve signals are crackles inside the brain; we project a blue sky up there. Every observation is already interpretation, and so is fallible.
n15: fallibilism
	summary=There are no authoritative sources and no reliable way to justify ideas as true. Not despair but the engine, expecting even your best ideas to contain error and trying to correct it.
n16: rejection of authority
	summary=Nullius in verba, take no one's word for it. A necessary condition for progress, but on its own not enough; usually new authorities simply replace the old.
n17: tradition of criticism
	summary=A rare kind of tradition whose point is to change ideas rather than preserve them, carrying them forward by exposing them to criticism. This is what actually made the difference.
n18: the Enlightenment
	summary=The rebellion against authority in knowledge that built institutions of criticism and began creating knowledge at a noticeable, accelerating rate.
n19: testability
	summary=A theory must make predictions that could be contradicted by some observation, Popper's criterion of demarcation. Necessary, but the prophet and the gambler are testable too.
n20: bad explanation
	summary=An explanation easy to vary while still fitting the appearances. Its details are barely connected to the phenomenon, so it can absorb any result and explains nothing.
n21: good explanation
	summary=An explanation hard to vary, because every detail does functional work; change a detail and the account breaks. This, not testability, was the decisive factor.
n22: realism
	summary=The common-sense and true doctrine that the physical world really exists and is accessible to reason, so that explanations of it can exist too.
n23: instrumentalism
	summary=The misconception that science can only predict observations, never describe the reality behind them. It denies that explanation exists at all.
n24: the seasons
	summary=Why is there winter? The phenomenon that both the Greek myths and modern physics set out to explain.
n25: the Persephone myth
	summary=Demeter grieves while Persephone visits Hades, so the world goes cold. Testable, yet you can swap Freyr, swap the magic seed, even flip it to escape-and-revenge, and it fits just as well.
n26: the axis-tilt theory
	summary=Earth's axis is tilted relative to its orbit, so each hemisphere leans toward the sun for half the year. Every detail does work; you cannot swap the moon for the sun or add a god's feelings.
n27: reach
	summary=The ability of some explanations to solve problems far beyond the ones they were created to solve. Not extrapolation, but fixed by the content of the explanation itself.
n28: out-of-phase seasons
	summary=From scraps of one hemisphere's evidence, axis-tilt predicts six-month polar days, no seasons at the tropics, and southern seasons exactly out of phase, places its makers never saw.
n29: knowledge growth
	summary=Sustained, accelerating creation of knowledge with ever-increasing reach, what began, uniquely in history, with the Enlightenment.
n30: the beginning of infinity
	summary=The open-ended possibility opened by explanations with reach under a tradition of criticism, an unlimited potential to create further knowledge.
